description: Quails are small ground-dwelling birds often found in grasslands and agricultural areas, feeding on seeds and insects.
They are commonly hunted and also kept as poultry in some regions.
The quokka is a small marsupial from Western Australia known for its friendly appearance and rounded face.
It forages on vegetation and is mostly nocturnal.
The resplendent quetzal is a colorful bird of Central American cloud forests, prized for its vibrant plumage.
They feed on fruit and small animals and are culturally significant in the region.
The quagga was a subspecies of plains zebra with distinct striping only on the front of the body; it is now extinct.
Historical records and preserved skins inform its appearance and biology.
Quolls are carnivorous marsupials native to Australia and New Guinea, feeding on small vertebrates and invertebrates.
They occupy a range of habitats including forests and grasslands.
